My right eye has a large "blood shot" area that wasn't there until I took the vaccine also. I was found to still have a count of "34" on my Covid antibody blood test. The ED physician stated that was probably the reason I had the reaction was because I still had antibodies. I tested positive for Covid on Sept 19, 2020 and took the vaccine #1 1/11/2021 (almost 120 days from positive Covid test). If I had known I was going to have any type of reaction because I still had antibodies, I would have waited a few more weeks/months to get the vaccine. This should really be looked into. I am now very scared to receive the 2nd vaccine because of the side effects that has been reported after the 2nd vaccine. I really need good advice about what to do about 2nd vaccine.

Initially, I had severe arm and back pain that lasted 3-4 days.  On day 1-2, I was extremely exhausted, so exhausted that I actually wet the bed and I have NEVER wet the bed as an adult, which was extremely embarrassing.  The worst part is, since the shot, day 1, my eye has been twitching. I have been reporting it .  I do not think it is just a coincidence anymore like I originally thought.  I have had eye twitches in the past but they have never lasted this long!  It has been 3 weeks and there is no end in sight.  The time between twitches is sometimes less, but the severity of the twitching is getting more intense, sometimes causing my eye to blink (although usually its a lateral upper eyelid twitch) and I have had 1-2 instances of my upper lip twitching along with it (within the last couple of days).  The eye is driving me crazy.  I can't fall asleep at night because it keeps me awake and it twitches when I'm trying to fall asleep.  There has been nothing that has changed in terms of increased stress, increased caffeine consumption, decreased sleep, etc. to have explained this persistent eye twitching.  I did have my annual eye exam on 1/15/2021 and talked to him about it and he said we will continue to watch it.  It was just annoying at first but it will not go away and like I said, the intensity and pulsating of the twitch is getting progressively worse.

Patient is a 10-month-old male born at 37 weeks with a history of aortic coarctation s/p surgical repair and angioplasty, left vocal cord hypomobility, and prior episodes of stridor, who presented to ED on 1/7 with 1 day of progressive respiratory distress. He was found to have significant tracheal stenosis during this hospitalization.    He presented with symptoms of progressively noisy breathing and muted voice which culminated in an episode of severe respiratory distress with increased secretions and work of breathing. He previously had been on a thickened diet but was cleared by OT to take un-thickened breastmilk after a swallow study had been reassuring against aspiration in June. In the week prior, he had also been transitioned from a preemie nipple to larger size nipple. On the day of presentation, he had also incidentally received his 2nd flu shot prior to respiratory decompensation.    In the ED he had oxygen saturation in the low 70s, pronounced work of breathing with tracheal tugging, intercostal and subcostal retractions, and biphasic stridor. He had significant improvement after 1 dose of racemic epi, dexamethasone, and initiation of high-flow nasal cannula on 8 L at 40% FiO2. He was initially transitioned to the floor, but soon became significantly more agitated, tachycardic to the 180s, with recurrence of significant work of breathing, coarse lung sounds, intermittent stridor, self-resolving desaturation to the low 80s.  He was given an additional dose of racemic epinephrine due to concern for possible atypical presentation of anaphylaxis. Vital signs improved but given recurrence of respiratory distress, he was transferred to the PICU.   In the PICU he received 2 further doses of dexamethasone and two nighttime doses of racemic epinephrine for initial concern for croup.  He did not have any further episodes of respiratory distress, continued to improve symptomatically, and vitals stabilized. ENT performed bedside laryngoscopy which revealed a posterior vocal fold notch concerning for glottic and/or subglottic stenosis. He was transferred to the floor on 1/10.   Due to concern for aspiration, on 1/11 Pt underwent a video fluoroscopic swallow study, at which time he was found to have fatigue-related pharyngeal phase dysphagia, vocal fold hypomobility, and VF notch. He also had baseline chest rattle and congestion that increased during feeding. These findings were concerning for potential aspiration, so OT recommended returning to half nectar-thickened feeds. On 1/12 ENT performed an exam under anesthesia with micro laryngoscopy and bronchoscopy which revealed complete tracheal rings and severe tracheal narrowing to 2.9 mm.  CT angiogram on 01/13 was consistent with complete tracheal rings and did not show evidence of vascular ring or extrinsic compression by a mediastinal mass.  Pulmonology was consulted and recommended albuterol (for mucus clearance) and CPT/clapping twice daily, and recommended discharge with racemic epinephrine to be used only in case of respiratory emergency while concurrently calling 911. An EpiPen was also provided as an emergency precaution. After joint decision-making with ENT and family, Pt was discharged home on 01/15 for continued discussion of surgical planning for a slide tracheoplasty.  Pt will also follow-up with pulmonology in 4-8 weeks after discharge. He will need pre-operative CHO and outpatient visit with his cardiologist.  He will need a repeat VFSS in 4-6 months. He is already established for feeding therapy
HISTORY: H/o aortic coarctation s/p repair including repeat valvuloplasty Eczema Stridor Peanut/dairy allergy

On the afternoon of 01/19/2021 this patient called Health Department to report that she started experiencing "drawing and tightening of the lips" about 9:30pm on 01/18/2021.  Pt stated fear of having a stroke and presented to Emergency Department soon after.  Patient stated was informed by the ED physician that patient possibly had Bell's Palsy related to the COVID-19 vaccine received (01/13/2021).  Pt described that symptoms had "mostly" resolved by time she left the ED after midnight and that was completely resolved when awakened from normal sleep at 7:00am today.    This RN obtained patient's visit note from the 01/18/2021 event.  Summary as follows:  Pt presented to Emergency Department with complaint of perioral paresthesia and earlier in the evening that sides of mouth "drew up."  Pt feared stroke and presented to ED.  Mild paresthesia persisted.  Neurological exam was negative. No unilateral deficits. Speech intact. NIH Stroke scale was 0.  MD's note states patient was advised that the symptoms could be associated with hyperventilation syndrome or could be early manifestation of Bell's palsy with the recent vaccine administration (five days earlier).  Pt was discharged from the ED without finding anything to indicate need for further work up or admission or the presence of an unstable medical condition.  Pt was reminded to take BP med as prescribed due to patient stating had not yet taken evening med dose.
LAB_DATA: ECG - normal CT scan of head - normal

Since receiving the first vaccine I first had arm pain, but only for the first day or two.  Then a couple of days later I realized that I had low grain headaches (which never have), sneezing, running nose, and feeling flushed.  What clued me in to paying more attention to these symptoms:  I found myself two days in a row opening windows (in winter) because I was feeling hot/flushed and since I almost never have a fever, it took me a day to figure out that the hot/flushed feeling, plus other symptoms was probably a low grade reaction to the vaccination.  A week later, I remain stuffed up but the headache is going away and I have not felt flushed yesterday or today.
LAB_DATA: I did not go to see a doctor, given the low grade nature of the symptoms, but I do believe them a reaction.  I am somewhat concerned about the second shot given this week long response, but am hoping this means the reaction to the follow up vaccination will be less.
HISTORY: High blood pressure, Type 2 Diabetes; proteinuria (only one kidney); six different cancers over time:  parotid gland;  melanoma (twice); kidney cancer; prostate cancer (prostate removed); multiple skin cancers.  Both appendix and gall bladder moved during second surgery for kidney cancer.
